Analyzing Predictors of Marathon Time¶

By: Sohan Ganatra and Eamon Plante¶

Introduction¶

Former 5000m and 10000m world record holder and number 2 all time marathon runner, Kenenisa Bekele (left) with number 9 all time 5000m runner and current marathon world record holder, Eliud Kipchoge (right)

Motivation¶

As recreational distance runners and fans of professional distance running, we were interested in using data to shed light on phenomena in our favorite sport. One interesting conversation among distance running athletes and fans is how individual athletes perform over many different distance events. The Olympic distances at the professional level for track and field are the 1500m, the 5000m, and the 10000m. In road running, the Olympic distance is the Marathon. Typically as runners age they move up to longer distances where the aerobic strength accumulated over a long career is more advantageous than leg speed which peaks for most runners in their mid 20s. This move can happen earlier in an athletes career too, however. American distance runner Conner Mantz debuted in the Marathon at just 26 years old when he was arguably in peak 5k or 10k shape. It matters which events professional runners choose to compete in when prize money and contracts are on the line. Many runners figure that being comparatively better at the 10,000m and the half marathon than the 5k might mean they should prememptively move up to the marathon to play to their percieved strengths and be a competetive as possible on the world stage. In the case of Conner Mantz, it is likely that after narrowly missing out on a spot on team USA in the 5000m and 10000m, he decided his time would be better spent at the marathon which is a less competitive event in the USA.

We wanted to see how performance at shorter distances can indicate performance in the marathon. Understanding how good Conner Mantz intuition is about transistioning to marathon running or how current 10000m stars like Joshua Cheptegei and Grant Fisher might perform in the marathon is incredibly interesting to the running community. People often argue whether specialization in different events really makes a big difference in performance or if just being fast in general indicates running faster over a variety of distances. Ideally, we wanted to create a model that could reasonably predict a professional runners marathon time based on their times at shorter distances.

The Dataset¶

Our dataset is made up of multiple tables retrieved from the Alltime Athletics website, a website containing a large set of up to date race results. We originally found this through a dataset on Kaggle. However, the dataset on Kaggle was not fully up to date so we decided to scrape the data directly from the source website.

We used the top performances table for the 1500m, 3000m, 5000m, 10000m, Half Marathon, and Marathon. Each dataset contains the name of ranking of the performance, the result time, the name of the athlete, the athlete's nationality, the athlete's date of birth, the position the athlete finished in, the location of the race, and the date of the race.

Part 1: Gathering Data¶

Scraping The Data¶

To begin, we had get the data from the website into a usable format. Since we did not have a formatted file like a csv ready to read the data from, we had to start by scraping the data from the website.

The first thing we noticed was that the data was not held in a table within the html. It was all in a long text string. Irregularities in the data brought up many challenges in parsing the string. Some columns had data that was more than one word, so we could not simply break the string into words and fill the dataframe from there. Additionally, some columns were blank, which we aso had to account for that when parsing the string into data.

The following are methods that helped parse the string into data and create a dataframe.

In [32]:
def identifier(a): # takes in an array of strings and returns it as a list 
                   # with sublists containing the values a row
    rowends = []
    rowstarts = []
    rowstarts.append(0)
    count = 0
    i = 0
    # Uses the date as a point for starting new lines, because each row contains a formatted date
    while i < len(a):
        if re.search("\d\d\.\d\d\.\d\d\d\d", a[i]):
            rowends.append(i)
            if (i + 1) < len(a):
                rowstarts.append(i + 1)
        i += 1
    rows = []
    
    for i in range(0, len(rowends)):
        rowi = [] #initial row list
        rown = [] #rows with names corrected
        rowb = [] #rows with dates corrected assuming names are right
        rowl = [] #rows with location corrected assuming names and birthdays are right
        
        # make rowi
        for j in range(rowstarts[i], rowends[i] + 1):
            rowi.append(a[j])
            j += 1
        
        # combine names
        j = 0
        while j < len(rowi):
            if j == 2:
                rown.append(rowi[j])
                j += 1
                while not (re.search("[A-Z][A-Z][A-Z]", rowi[j])):
                    rown[2] = rown[2] + " " + rowi[j]
                    j += 1
            else:
                rown.append(rowi[j])
                j += 1
        
        # fix dates
        j = 0
        while j < len(rown):
            if j == 4:
                if re.search("\d\d\.\d\d\.\d\d", rown[j]):
                    rowb.append(rown[j])
                    j += 1
                else:
                    if re.search("[A-Z][a-z]*", rown[j + 1]):
                        rowb.append("-")
                        rowb.append(rown[j])
                        j += 1
                    else:
                        rowb.append("-")
                        j += 1
                        
            else:
                rowb.append(rown[j])
                j += 1
        
        # combine locations
        j = 0
        while j < len(rowb):
            if j == 6:
                rowl.append(rowb[j])
                j += 1
                while j < len(rowb) and not (re.search("\d\d\.\d\d\.\d\d\d\d", rowb[j])):
                    rowl[6] = rowl[6] + " " + rowb[j]
                    j += 1
            else:
                rowl.append(rowb[j])
                j += 1
        
        rows.append(rowl)
            
    return rows


def df_event(soup): # Takes in the BeautifulSoup object and returns a datafram
    # All of the data we want is in a <pre> tag, so we find that directly
    string = soup.find('pre')
    string = string.get_text()
    rows = string.split() # Split text on whitespace
    rows = identifier(rows) # Call above identifier method which will format string into list of rows
    df = pd.DataFrame(columns=["Rank", "Time", "Name", "Country", "Date of Birth", "Place", "City", "Date"]) 
    #for i in range(0, len(rows_10)):
    #    if len(rows_10[i]) != 8:
    #        print(rows_10[i])
    for i in rows:
        df.loc[len(df.index)] = i
    return df

Cleaning The Data¶

Now that we have the off of the website placed into dataframes, we can tidy up some parts of it so that the data is easier to work with.

First off, we want to convert the times for the different distances into the same format, so they can be compared more easily. We added a column to each dataframe that would hold the time in seconds.

The methods below take in the time in various formats and return the time in seconds.

In [35]:
# Converts time from MM:SS.SS to seconds for 5000m and 10000m
def secs_510(time):
    if re.search("(\d\d):(\d\d\.\d\d?)", time):
        result = re.search("(\d\d):(\d\d\.\d\d?)", time)
        return (float(result.group(1)) * 60.0) + float(result.group(2))

# Converts time from MM:SS to seconds for half marathon
def secs_hm(time):
    if re.search("(\d\d):(\d\d)", time):
        result = re.search("(\d\d):(\d\d)", time)
        return (float(result.group(1)) * 60.0) + float(result.group(2))

# Converts time from M:SS.SS to seconds for 1500m and 3000m
def secs_153(time):
    if re.search("(\d):(\d\d\.\d\d?)", time):
        result = re.search("(\d):(\d\d\.\d\d?)", time)
        return (float(result.group(1)) * 60.0) + float(result.group(2))

# Converts time from H:MM:SS to seconds for marathon
def secs_m(time):
    if re.search("(\d):(\d\d):(\d\d)", time):
        result = re.search("(\d):(\d\d):(\d\d)", time)
        return (float(result.group(1)) * 60.0 * 60.0) + (float(result.group(2)) * 60.0) + float(result.group(3))

# Adding the time in seconds to a new column in each dataframe
df_10['Time_Sec'] = df_10["Time"].map(lambda element : secs_510(element))
df_15['Time_Sec'] = df_15["Time"].map(lambda element : secs_153(element))
df_hm['Time_Sec'] = df_hm["Time"].map(lambda element : secs_hm(element))
df_5['Time_Sec'] = df_5["Time"].map(lambda element : secs_510(element))
df_m['Time_Sec'] = df_m["Time"].map(lambda element : secs_m(element))
df_3['Time_Sec'] = df_3["Time"].map(lambda element : secs_153(element))

Next, we wanted to make an alternate dataframe for each dataset that would hold the top performers (just each person's fastest time in the table) rather than all of the top performances. As mentioned above, the original dataset conatains all of the top performaces, including multiple performaces by the same athlete. Initially, we will want to only look at each athlete's best performance, since we will be looking at how an athlete's peak ability in shorter events can predict their best time in the marathon. Our data also is limited and we can not guaruntee to have the same number of performances from each athlete. Some athletes have a lot of performances on the top table and some have only one. Having different numbers of permformance from the different athletes could skew data.

So we made a PB (personal best) table that keep only the top time for each athlete and removes duplicates on name. We also added a new column with rank which contains the new rank in the top performers table.

In [36]:
def rank_pbs(df): # Method adds the new rank to the table
    df = df.drop(columns = ['Rank']).reset_index().drop(columns = ['index']).reset_index()
    df['Rank'] = df['index'].apply(lambda elem : elem + 1)
    df = df.drop(columns = ['index'])
    return df

# Drops duplicates entries on name and passes into the rank_pbs method to add the new rank
df_10_pb = rank_pbs(df_10.drop_duplicates(subset = ['Name']))
df_15_pb = rank_pbs(df_15.drop_duplicates(subset = ['Name']))
df_hm_pb = rank_pbs(df_hm.drop_duplicates(subset = ['Name']))
df_m_pb = rank_pbs(df_m.drop_duplicates(subset = ['Name']))
df_5_pb = rank_pbs(df_5.drop_duplicates(subset = ['Name']))
df_3_pb = rank_pbs(df_3.drop_duplicates(subset = ['Name']))

Right away, we see a few obvious things highlighted by the plots. Looking at the two shortest distances, 3000m and 1500m, there is a big drop off in number of data points, and a far weaker correlation, if any. This means there are not that many athletes who have a top time in both the 1500m or 3000m and the marathon. The jump from these middle distance events to the marathon is very large, and those specializing to be top performers at middle distance are not as often going to be top performers in the marathon as well. The lack of data matching both events leads us to believe that the shorter distances can be a good indicator of marathon performance.

There are far more matched data points for the longer distances, meaning a lot of the top performers in the events from 5000m to Half Marathon are also top performers in the marathon. Because of this, going forward we will be focusing on the data from the three longer ditances, 5000m, 10000m, and Half Marathon.

In the top three plots, we see a positive correlation between 5000m, 10000m, and Half Marathon times and Marathon times. This is in line with what we expected to see. While the events are different distances, higher performing runners in general will perform better regardless of the distance within long distance running.

Consistancy Metric¶

While rank gave us a more standardized comparison between the events, we wanted to be able to have a standard way to compare the performances in the different events based on time. We decided to create a standardized metric that would be based on times instead of place. Another consideration we thought of was consistancy. The top performer's rankings are based on the athlete's personal best time. But we also wanted to factor in the number of top performances an athlete had posted. For example, if someone has run consistantly run fast times, that could indicate better overall performance than someone who has run an exceptionally fast time just once but could not recreate it. That said, we still want to value faster performances higher than slower ones. Someone who has five performances in the top 50 indicates better performance than someone who has run 5 performances in the bottom of the table.

To achieve this we created a metric that we call consistancy score. First we split split up the times into five bins by splitting the range of times in the data into 5 even intervals. For every performance an athlete had in the fastest bin, they get 5 points. For every performance in the second fasteset bin they get 4 points, and so on down to 1 point. This way an athlete gets rated higher based on both faster performances and repeating those fast performances.

The way the score was calculated was by taking the performers from the top perfomers (PB) table, checking their performances in the all top performances table.

For the consistency score, we also decided to limit the data. Since all the datasets were of different size, having more performers for certain distances would skew the points. Based on the smallest dataset, we decided to go with only the top 500 performers.

The following methods add up the score this way for each athlete in the table for each event.

In [39]:
def total_points_5(name): # Takes an athlete name as input and calculates their consistency score for the 5000m
    
    def points_5(time): # Helper function determines points for a given time.
        # The ranges were identified by cutting dataframe in a seperate step
        # and then printing the unique values in the interval column created in
        # the cutting process.
        if 755.32 < time <= 763.354:
            return 5
        elif 763.354 < time <= 771.348:
            return 4
        elif 771.348 < time <= 779.342:
            return 3
        elif 779.342 < time <= 787.336:
            return 2
        elif 787.336 < time <= 795.33:
            return 1
        else:
            return 0
    
    # Filters the original dataframe containing all of the top performances
    # to just the athlete in question
    df_5_person = df_5[df_5['Name'] == name]
    points = 0
    # Loops over the times for this person and give totals their score.
    for i in df_5_person['Time_Sec'].values:
        points = points + points_5(i)
    return points

def total_points_10(name): # Takes an athlete name as input and calculates their consistency score for the 10000m
    def points_10(time):
        if 1570.909 < time <= 1589.234:
            return 5
        elif 1589.234 < time <= 1607.468:
            return 4
        elif 1607.468 < time <= 1625.702:
            return 3
        elif 1625.702 < time <= 1643.936:
            return 2
        elif 1643.936 < time <= 1662.17:
            return 1
        else:
            return 0
    
    df_10_person = df_10[df_10['Name'] == name]
    points = 0
    for i in df_10_person['Time_Sec'].values:
        points = points + points_10(i)
    return points

def total_points_hm(name): # Takes an athlete name as input and calculates their consistency score for the Half Marathon
    def points_hm(time):
        if 3450.817 < time <= 3487.6:
            return 5
        elif 3487.6 < time <= 3524.2:
            return 4
        elif 3524.2 < time <= 3560.8:
            return 3
        elif 3560.8 < time <= 3597.4:
            return 2
        elif 3597.4 < time <= 3634.0:
            return 1
        else:
            return 0
    
    df_hm_person = df_hm[df_hm['Name'] == name]
    points = 0
    for i in df_hm_person['Time_Sec'].values:
        points = points + points_hm(i)
    return points

We were surprised to see the clustering of results on the low end of the consistancy scale. This likely highlights a flaw in the metric that we did not originally realize. There a lot of people towards a bottom of the tables that have few or only one performance in the table. Based on this, we decided to no longer consider consistancy in our a prediction model. As seen by the uneven distribution and lack of correlation to marathon time, it is not a good factor in this context for indicating marathon performances.

Part 3: Can we use this data to predict marathon performances?¶

Given this analysis, we wanted to see what metrics would be the most effective indicators of success in the marathon, as well as see if we could create a model that would reliably predict marathon success in athletes.

Fitting a Linear Regression¶

We decided to start with a linear regression model on the data comparing the shorter distance times to the marathon times. From the plots above, there seems to be the strongest correlation when directly comparing the times.

We fit the regression to the data, and then used it to predict each athlete's marathon time based on their 5000m, 10000m, and Half Marathon time. For each we made a new datafram that contains a column of the predictions. We then added a column that calculated the residuals. The residuals are how much the model's predicted marathon time was off of the athlete's actual marathon time.

In [42]:

Residuals on this graph are an athletes Marathon PB - their predicted Marathon PB. A negative residual then means that the model predicted more seconds (a slower time) than the actual time. The model for the 5000m is by far the least consistent across time whereas the half marathon and the 10000m are less varied. All three models trended toward predicting slower than reality as time increases.

Conclusion¶

Understanding¶

This exploration has confirmed that there is a relationship times in the 5000m, 10000m, and Half Marathon and times in the Marathon but more importantly it has shown the challenges of making an accurate model to predict success in the marathon. As we saw, measures of top time, rank, and the consistency of an athlete alone were not enough to accurately predict Marathon time. There are many more variables to consider, such as how old an athlete is when they run their top marathon. Another assumption of this investigation which is clearly problematic in hindsight is the assumption that all times were run under the same conditions. One runner who has a personal best in the 10000m of 27:00 is not necessarily more fit than a runner with a personal best of 27:30 who ran that on a much hotter or windier day for example. Our model would predict that the former would be faster when in reality they were the same or they the former was slower. This speaks to a larger difficulty in trying to predict human performance. Athletes do not have uniform access to training and race opportunities across time and across the world. Factoring in conditions to both the input times and the marathon times of a training set may be able to give a model that accurately predicts marathon potential. In other words, what an athlete would be able to run on the easiest course in the optimal weather conditions. One take away for athletes and coaches is that the relationship between 5000m, 10000m, and Half Marathon success is not so strong that an athlete should rule out success in the longer distance before trying it out.

Future Considerations¶

This tutorial serves as a good launching pad for further investigation into this topic. Several of the considerations that were outside of the scope of this project are above such as racing conditions or an age-grading score. Matching date and city data from performances to weather data might be a good start for factoring in condition. Creating a score for weather conditions could be used to normalize performances. Furthermore, the corresponding data set for the women's racing catagory is here at http://www.alltime-athletics.com/women.htm. Recreating these steps with that data would be a worthwile experiment. The World Athletics site, while easier to scrape, does not have all its data organized as well, but might still be able to provide data points that are not easily available with this dataset such as times for each athletes debut marathon which can be compared with their marathon personal best. It is unfortunate that training data for these elite athletes is a closely guarded secret in the vast majority of cases since that would also be very interesting to analyze.

Understanding the relationships among these metrics as well as the ones revealed above is very helpful in helping professional athletes and coaches as well as amateurs navigate the sport. It is unlikely however that there will be enough data in the near future to create a model to accurately predict an athletes potential in an event due to all the factors that impact performance.
